            <section id="Illegal_Logging">
                <h2>Illegal Logging</h2>
                <p>
                    Illegal logging refers to the unlawful act of cutting down, transporting, or trading in timber or
                    forest products without proper authorization, often resulting in environmental degradation,
                    deforestation, and the loss of biodiversity.
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <h3>How to recognize:</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li><p><strong>Lack of proper documentation:</strong> Illegal loggers often lack the required
                        permits, licenses, or documentation for logging operations. They may not have legal authorization
                        or fail to provide necessary paperwork when requested.</p></li>
                        <li><p><strong>Presence of unauthorized logging activities:</strong> Keep an eye out for logging
                        activities in protected areas, national parks, or other restricted zones where logging is
                        prohibited. Unauthorized loggers may try to operate in these areas to exploit valuable timber
                        resources.</p></li>
                        <li><p><strong>Suspicious transport or storage of timber:</strong> Illegal loggers may transport
                        or store timber in unconventional ways or without proper documentation. Look for signs of unmarked
                        trucks or vehicles carrying large amounts of timber without clear ownership or traceability.</p></li>
                        <li><p><strong>Lack of environmental considerations:</strong> Illegal loggers often disregard
                        environmental regulations and sustainability practices. They may not implement measures to mitigate
                        environmental impacts or avoid sensitive habitats, such as protected forests or endangered species
                        habitats.</p></li>
                        <li><p><strong>Involvement of organized crime:</strong> Illegal logging is often associated with
                        organized criminal networks involved in timber smuggling, corruption, or money laundering. Look for
                        signs of criminal activity, such as armed guards, suspicious individuals, or connections to other
                        illegal activities.</p></li>
                    </ul>
                    <h3>Resources:</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li><a href="https://www.denr.gov.ph/"><p>Department of Environment and Natural Resources (DENR)</p></a></li>
                    </ul>
                </ul>
